            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#martaf">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Στατειλία</name> <name>Θε<lb n="2" break="no"/>αγενὶς</name></persName> <w>ἔζ<hi rend="small">η</hi><lb n="3" break="no"/>σε<unclear>ν</unclear></w> <space quantity="1" unit="character"/> <w>ἔτη</w>
                    <lb n="4"/><num><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></num>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp><app><note>Text based on photographs</note></app></listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>Stateilia Theagenis lived for [?] years.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Statilia Theagenis visse [?] anni.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The epitaph presents the name of the deceased and the indication of her age (the years are assumed to be in a missing fourth line). The gentilicium <foreign xml:lang="grc">Στατείλια</foreign> is also found in the Latin funerary inscription of the 2nd-3rd century CE, CIL 10.7094 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000376">ISic000376</ref>. The name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Θεαγενίς</foreign> is not well attested (for the masculine form <foreign xml:lang="grc">Θεαγένης</foreign> attested in South Italy, see LGPN 3A 199). For <foreign xml:lang="grc">Θεαγενίς</foreign> in two urban inscriptions, see Solin 1982: 84.</p>
            </div>
